{"type":"message","id":"9d73cc2c","parentId":"2bc6f377","timestamp":"2026-05-07T15:56:05.528Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The output shows \"60\" - so the GPU is at 60%! But there's also this WSL/UNC path warning in stderr. The subprocess.getoutput is capturing both stdout and stderr mixed together. So the `r.strip()` result is `\"60\"` (the GPU percentage) but it gets concatenated with the warning text.\n\nThe issue is the `repr(r2.strip())` shows `\"60\"` - that means `r2.strip()` = \"60\" exactly. So the first line `via shell: '\"\\\\nCMD.EXE...'` shows a full repr. That full string contains \"60\" somewhere.\n \nI think I see what's happening - the stderr warning is getting prepended to the stdout output, so when I strip and repr the result, I'm getting both pieces of output combined together as one string. So the real issue is that `subprocess.getoutput()` is capturing both stdout and stderr merged together, which is why I'm getting that warning message concatenated with the GPU percentage. When I check if the result is a digit, \"60\" followed by a newline and warning text won't pass the `.isdigit()` test, so I need to extract just the actual number from the mixed output. The simplest fix would be to either use `shell=True` to run through cmd.exe with proper redirection, or parse the output to extract only the numeric part before the warning message appears.","thinkingSignature":"0bb5e925c3e8320bdd7f33f6d12c725e1ff9b13e2484327becbc7b32dad33e06"},{"type":"text","text":"\n\n\n...\n\nThe GPU is actually running at 60%! The issue is the WSL/UNC warning in stderr is getting mixed with the output, so `isdigit()` fails.\n\nLet me fix the extraction properly:\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_5916poiwetm4_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"sed -n '86,95p' /home/apinan/.openclaw/workspace/sysmon.py"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":398,"output":370,"cac