{"type":"message","id":"6a99d741","parentId":"eb82a834","timestamp":"2026-05-07T15:56:33.835Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"This is a Windows PE32+ executable. Running it from WSL runs it through WSL's path translation, which is causing the issue.\n\nBut when I run it from PowerShell directly (via `& $py script.py`), it worked fine! The problem is that the pythonw.exe I'm running is actually being run through some WSL mediation.\n\nWait, but it did output \"1\" which is the correct GPU percentage! The \"1\" is there but it's preceded by a CMD.EXE warning about UNC paths. Let me look at the output more carefully:\n\n```\n\"'\\\\wsl.localhost\\Ubuntu\\home\\apinan\\.openclaw\\workspace'\\nCMD.EXE was started with the above path as the current directory.\\nUNC paths are not supported.  Defaulting to Windows directory.\\n1\"\n```\n\nSo the GPU IS 1%! The issue is just that `subprocess.getoutput()` captures stderr too, and the warning message from CMD about UNC paths is getting included.\n\n\nThe error message is getting prepended to the output, so when I check if the result is a digit, it's actually a multi-line string starting with characters like quotes and newlines, not just \"1\". That's why the validation fails—the function sees all this extra text before reaching the actual GPU percentage value.\n\nI need to handle this by extracting just the numeric portion from the output, filtering out all the stderr noise. I'll split the result and grab only the part that looks like a valid GPU reading.\n","thinkingSignature":"10576fd35fd3a575ce8d99a90516bc430f1573977f7a3fd87675d19c7c2a9401"},{"type":"text","text":"\n\n\nตัวเลข `1` มีอยู่ในผลแล้ว แต่มี error text ติดมาด้วย ทำให้ `isdigit()` ตรวจไม่ผ่าน\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_crk4240o8uu1_1","name":"edit","arguments":{"edits":[{"newText":"# ── GPU ──\ndef get_gpu():\n    try:\n        if IS_WINDOWS:\n            r = subprocess.getoutput(r\"C:\\Windows\\System32\\nvi