{"type":"message","id":"cf4ca005","parentId":"5063d12e","timestamp":"2026-05-07T15:59:08.398Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"psutil is available on Windows Python. Good.\n\nNow let me redesign sysmon.py:\n1. Remove RAM row\n2. Keep CPU + GPU rows\n3. Add a 4th row showing top process (highest CPU or GPU usage)\n\nFor top process, I need to track GPU usage per process. That's harder - pynvml can give per-process GPU info.\n\nLet me think about this:\n- CPU top process: psutil.process_iter with cpu_percent()\n- GPU top process: pynvml.nvmlDeviceGetProcessUtilizationByHandle() or similar\n\nActually pynvml has `nvmlDeviceGetComputeRunningProcesses` which gives GPU utilization per process.\n\n\nI'll use psutil for the CPU top process and pynvml to find the GPU top process, then test both approaches to see which gives better results.","thinkingSignature":"c47a77325558cbe454b85b985e3a40770a49fb12ac91e4ba281c982ee20aaa1c"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_6119oie02981_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"\"/mnt/c/Windows/System32/WindowsPowerShell/v1.0/powershell.exe\" -Command \"\n\\$py = 'C:\\Users\\Apinan\\AppData\\Local\\Programs\\Python\\Python312\\python.exe'\n\\$tmp = \\\"\\$env:TEMP\\\\gputop.py\\\"\n@'\nimport pynvml\npynvml.nvmlInit()\nhandle = pynvml.nvmlDeviceGetHandleByIndex(0)\nprocs = pynvml.nvmlDeviceGetComputeRunningProcesses(handle)\nfor p in procs:\n    print('pid:', p.pid, 'gpu:', p.usedGpuMemory//1024//1024, 'MB')\npynvml.nvmlShutdown()\n'@ | Out-File -FilePath \\$tmp -Encoding utf8\n& \\$py \\$tmp\n\" 2>&1"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":151,"output":380,"cacheRead":99104,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":99635,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1778169542240,"responseId":"064be9c8a75187b3d8b5f5041566c7fe"}}
