{"type":"message","id":"963a46a8","parentId":"36c4fa9a","timestamp":"2026-05-07T16:03:31.594Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"So the nvmlComputeProcess struct only has `computeInstanceId`, `gpuInstanceId`, `pid`, `usedGpuMemory`. There is NO name field. So I must look up the name via `psutil.Process(p.pid).name()`.\n\nBut `usedGpuMemory` is `None` for all processes. So no process appears to be actively using GPU memory. That's why \"---\" shows up.\n\nThe real issue is: no process has `usedGpuMemory > 0`, which means no process is actively allocating GPU memory right now.\n\nI should try a different approach:\n1. Instead of GPU memory, use `nvmlDeviceGetProcessUtilizationByPids` (if available) to get per-process GPU usage\n\n\n2. Or fall back to `psutil.Process(pid).name()` for all compute processes and just show their names with the GPU utilization\n\nThe fundamental problem is that GPU utilization at 0-1% doesn't correlate cleanly to specific processes when memory allocation is zero. I need to try `nvmlDeviceGetProcessUtilizationByPids` to see if it can give me per-process GPU usage data instead.\n\nLooking at pynvml's API, I could call `nvmlDeviceGetComputeRunningProcesses` to get running processes and their GPU memory, then use `nvmlDeviceGetProcessUtilizationByPids` for utilization metrics if available. The core issue is that GPU utilization readings don't directly map to process names unless there's active memory allocation, so I should try querying both the process list and their individual utilization rates to find a better mapping. Actually the right answer might just be: there's no single process dominating GPU because GPU utilization is low (1% = system compositor/dwm). But for games or AI workloads, GPU util spikes and we should show the process.\n\nSo the approach should be: if GPU util > threshold (like 5%), show the process with highest usedGpuMemory. If not active, just say \"idle\".\n\nLet me update get_gpu_info to:\n1. Get GPU util\n2. If util > 5%: get top process by GPU memory, look up name via psutil\n3. Else: return \"idle\"\n\nBut there's still the None issue with usedGpuMemory.\n","thinkingSignature":"e34eff5b4325f115f3f6e79d063a5c05011b2691522cfc741740bdddd75e8a47"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_uwqeqlk05d2o_1","name":"socraticode__codebase_search","arguments":{"limit":5,"projectPath":"/home/apinan/.openclaw/workspace","query":"nvmlDeviceGetProcessUtilizationByPids gpu process utilization"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":339,"output":535,"cacheRead":106176,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":107050,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1778169798005,"responseId":"064beac8f6e0dc608b7733094fe38dd1"}}
{"type":"message","id":"771584ff","parentId":"963a46a8","timestamp":"2026-05-07T16:03:31.928Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_uwqeqlk05d2o_1","toolName":"socraticode__codebase_search","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Search results for \"nvmlDeviceGetProcessUtilizationByPids gpu process utilization\" (5 matches):\n\n--- sysmon.py (lines 59-87) [python] score: 1.0000 ---\n\ndef get_gpu_info():\n    if not _init_gpu():\n        return None, \"---\"\n    try:\n        import pynvml\n        h = pynvml.nvmlDeviceGetHandleByIndex(0)\n        util = pynvml.nvmlDeviceGetUtilizationRates(h)\n        # GPU processes — use name directly from nvml struct\n        gpu_procs = pynvml.nvmlDeviceGetComputeRunningProcesses(h)\n        names = []\n        for p in gpu_procs:\n            # name field available on compute process handle\n            name = getattr(p, \"name\", \"\") or \"\"\n            if name:\n                names.append(name[:20])\n        # deduplicate preserve order\n        seen = set()\n        unique = []\n        for n in names:\n            if n not in seen:\n                seen.add(n)\n                unique.append(n)\n        return int(util.gpu), \", \".join(unique[:2]) if unique else \"---\"\n    except Exception:\n        return None, \"---\"\n\ndef pct_col(p):\n    return \"#ff2222\" if p >= 90 else \"#ff8800\" if p >= 70 else \"#00ff88\"\n\n--- sysmon.py (lines 46-58) [python] score: 0.5000 ---\n\n# ── GPU via pynvml ──\n_gpu_init_ok = False\ndef _init_gpu():\n    global _gpu_init_ok\n    if not _gpu_init_ok:\n        try:\n            import pynvml\n            pynvml.nvmlInit()\n            _gpu_init_ok = True\n        except Exception:\n            _gpu_init_ok = False\n    return _gpu_init_ok\n\n--- sysmon.py (lines 141-150) [python] score: 0.3929 ---\n\ndef terminal_bar():\n    print(\"CPU/GPU monitor (Ctrl+C to exit)\")\n    while True:\n        cpu = get_cpu_win()\n        gpu, gpu_names = get_gpu_info()\n        cpu_name, cpu_val = get_top_cpu_proc()\n        g = f\" GPU {gpu:3d}% ({gpu_names})\" if gpu is not None else \" GPU  N/A\"\n        print(f\"\\r  {time.strftime('%H:%M:%S')}  CPU {cpu:5.1f}% ({cpu_name} {cpu_val:.0f}%){g}     \", end=\"\", flush=True)\n        time.sleep(1)\n\n--- skills/ufo-windows-automation/SKILL.md (lines 91-166) [markdown] score: 0.3333 ---\n3. Finds JSON object if stray text surrounds it\n4. **Lowercases all keys** (Observation → observation) for pydantic validation\n\nIf parsing fails after these fixes, UFO falls back to plain text mode.\n\n## API Configuration\n\nConfig file: `C:\\Users\\Apinan\\Tools\\UFO\\config\\ufo\\agents.yaml`\n\nCurrent working config (MiniMax):\n```yaml\nHOST_AGENT:\n  API_TYPE: \"openai\"\n  API_BASE: \"https://api.minimax.io/v1\"\n  API_MODEL: \"MiniMax-M2.7\"\n  API_KEY: \"***\"      # DO NOT PRINT\n  VISUAL_MODE: False    # MiniMax has no vision; keep off\n  TOP_P: 1.0\n  TEMPERATURE: 0.0\n```\n\nThe `VISUAL_MODE: False` is important because MiniMax-M2.7 is NOT a vision model. If you use a vision model later (e.g., GPT-4V, Gemini), set `VISUAL_MODE: True`.\n\n## Files Reference\n\n| File/Dir | Purpose |\n|----------|---------|\n| `run-ufo.ps1` | PowerShell wrapper for easy runs |\n| `config/ufo/agents.yaml` | API keys and model config (PRIVATE) |\n| `config/ufo/system.yaml` | System-wide settings (MAX_STEP, TIMEOUT, etc.) |\n| `ufo/utils/__init__.py` | JSON parser with think-block stripping |\n| `ufo/llm/openai.py` | OpenAI-compatible LLM client |\n| `ufo/agents/agent/app_agent.py` | AppAgent implementation |\n| `ufo/agents/processors/strategies/app_agent_processing_strategy.py` | Main processing strategy |\n| `logs/` | UFO run logs |\n\n## Common Workflows\n\n### Open app and do something\n```powershell\n.\\.venv\\Scripts\\python.exe -m ufo --task mytask --request \"Open Chrome and go to chatgpt.com\"\n```\n\n### Open specific app by name\n```powershell\n.\\.venv\\Scripts\\python.exe -m ufo --task mytask --request \"Open Notepad\"\n```\n\n### Automate ChatGPT Web (image generation)\n1. Open Chrome via UFO: `Open Chrome and go to <URL>`\n2. AppAgent will control Chrome via UIA\n3. For complex flows, use UFO's AppAgent with proper prompts\n\n## Debugging\n\n- **No response / hung**: Check if MiniMax API is accessible\n- **Wrong app selected**: Use `select_application_window` with exact app name\n- **Action not working**: May need `MAXIMIZE_WINDOW: Tru\n\n--- sysmon.py (lines 26-45) [python] score: 0.3111 ---\n\n# ── Windows top process (CPU) ──\ndef get_top_cpu_proc():\n    try:\n        import psutil\n        procs = []\n        for p in psutil.process_iter([\"name\", \"cpu_percent\"]):\n            try:\n                n = p.name()\n                c = p.cpu_percent(interval=0.05)\n                if c > 0.5:\n                    procs.append((c, n))\n            except:\n                pass\n        procs.sort(key=lambda x: x[0], reverse=True)\n        if procs:\n            return procs[0][1][:20], procs[0][0]\n    except:\n        pass\n    return \"---\", 0\n"}],"details":{"mcpServer":"socraticode","mcpTool":"codebase_search"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1778169811928}}
{"type":"message","id":"2960c817","parentId":"771584ff","timestamp":"2026-05-07T16:03:43.505Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Let me just use psutil to find the GPU process name for processes that are actively running. But psutil doesn't have GPU info.\n\nInstead, I could look at all running processes and pick the one that makes sense - like checking for ComfyUI, Ollama, Chrome with GPU acceleration, etc.\n\nOR - I can query nvidia-smi directly using `subprocess.run` with `shell=True` and parse the output. This is more reliable since nvidia-smi gives process names directly.\n\nLet me try:\n```python\nr = subprocess.run(\n    ['nvidia-smi', '--query-compute-apps=pid,process_name,used_memory', '--format=csv,noheader'],\n    capture_output=True, text=True, shell=True\n)\n```\n\n\nI'll add error handling and parse the output if the command succeeds.","thinkingSignature":"cb4d4d3a5447d7e00f24abcdcfae7448e442d06615192fe82e7fe274fada42c9"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_fz6kx7gkjkqt_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"\"/mnt/c/Windows/System32/cmd.exe\" /c \"nvidia-smi --query-compute-apps=pid,process_name,used_memory --format=csv,noheader 2>nul\" 2>&1 | head -5"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":1421,"output":244,"cacheRead":106496,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":108161,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1778169811936,"responseId":"064bead611519d24b31a397267140d5c"}}
