{"type":"message","id":"82542703","parentId":"2bea7505","timestamp":"2026-05-07T16:03:56.497Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The WSL UNC path issue is still there because the Python subprocess is calling via WSL. But `nvidia-smi` from Windows CMD works and shows process names. I need to call it via subprocess with `shell=True` and explicitly via `cmd.exe`.\n\nActually the issue is that subprocess.getoutput() on Windows Python goes through WSL even when we specify Windows paths. We need `subprocess.run(..., shell=True)` or better yet, use `subprocess.Popen` with `shell=True`.\n\nBut in this case, the nvidia-smi output is showing \"Insufficient Permissions\" for many processes and used_memory is [N/A] everywhere. This means:\n\n\n1. No process is currently using GPU (all [N/A])\n2. So there's no meaningful GPU process name to show\n\nLet me try calling nvidia-smi directly from Windows Python with shell=True to bypass the WSL wrapping.\n","thinkingSignature":"e33710af56fd8a7c6d067e27197c3ee1dcec080e900ec9c8247a492890e646b4"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_goui4xj0hvwx_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"\"/mnt/c/Windows/System32/WindowsPowerShell/v1.0/powershell.exe\" -Command \"\n\\$py = 'C:\\Users\\Apinan\\AppData\\Local\\Programs\\Python\\Python312\\python.exe'\n\\$tmp = \\\"\\$env:TEMP\\\\ngputest.py\\\"\n@'\nimport subprocess\n# Force via cmd.exe explicitly\nr = subprocess.getoutput('cmd /c nvidia-smi --query-compute-apps=pid,process_name,used_memory --format=csv,noheader')\nprint(repr(r[:200]))\n'@ | Out-File -FilePath \\$tmp -Encoding utf8\n& \\$py \\$tmp\n\" 2>&1"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":328,"output":352,"cacheRead":108064,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":108744,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1778169827714,"responseId":"064beae61b064277175cb997499af7e5"}}
