{"type":"message","id":"31de12b1","parentId":"b3e36870","timestamp":"2026-05-07T16:12:34.155Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The labels have different fonts (14 vs 13) and pady (3 vs 3). They have different text lengths:\n- cpu_lbl: \"CPU : ---%\" (11 chars)\n- cpu_name_lbl: \"---\" (3 chars)\n\nThe labels are packed with `fill=\"x\"` and same `padx=10` and `anchor=\"w\"` (left-aligned), so they should align. But the font sizes differ, which might cause visual misalignment.\n\nBut wait — the actual display text that gets updated uses:\n- cpu_lbl: `f\"CPU : {cpu:5.1f}%\"` — same text always\n\n\n- cpu_name_lbl: `f\"  {cpu_name} {cpu_val:.0f}%\"` — starts with 2 spaces\n\nSo the name line has a couple spaces to compensate for missing \"CPU : \" prefix. The real issue is that cpu_lbl text is 11 characters but name_lbl only starts with that padding — I need to figure out how tkinter actually handles character spacing with proportional fonts versus monospaced ones.\n\nThe user specifically wants the position to match, not just the font size. With `fill=\"x\"` and `anchor=\"w\"` (west/left), both labels should start at the same x position, but I'm noticing the pady values are identical for both labels at 3 pixels, which is good. Let me verify this is actually producing the alignment they want. Looking at the text updates, both labels start at the same left edge with `anchor=\"w\"` and identical `padx=10`, so the actual display text should align properly. I'm wondering if the issue is that the default text length differs—\"CPU : ---%\" is longer than just \"---\"—so the initial display looks misaligned, but once the values update they should match up. The issue is likely font rendering differences between the two text elements. I should use a monospaced font consistently across all labels so character widths are predictable, and ensure the text updates align properly with padding adjustments.\n\nActually, I'm overcomplicating this—the user said the positions aren't equal, which suggests both labels need to start at the same x position. With `anchor=\"w\"` and the same padding, that should already be the case, but maybe the label widget widths themselves are different. Let me try consolidating the information into a single line per metric instead.\n\nThe cleanest approach is to merge each metric with its value on one line, so \"CPU : X% (name)\" shows everything together. This eliminates the positioning problem entirely since there's only one label per metric. Let me restructure the layout.\n","thinkingSignature":"45920ee607958d55b31c78ab06e81331c9222b8f1d1520a3a6a1bac35c03fcce"},{"type":"text","text":"\n\n\n...\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_pubuesz03ip5_1","name":"write","arguments":{"content":"#!/usr/bin/env python3\n\"\"\"Floating CPU/GPU monitor — always-on-top overlay.\"\"\"\nimport sys, os, time, ctypes\n\nIS_WINDOWS = os.name == \"nt\"\n\n# ── Windows CPU ──\ndef get_cpu_win():\n    try:\n        k = ctypes.windll.kernel32\n        class FT(ctypes.Structure):\n            _fields_ = [(\"dwLow\", ctypes.c_ulong), (\"dwHigh\", ctypes.c_ulong)]\n        idle, kern, user = FT(), FT(), FT()\n        k.GetSystemTimes(ctypes.byref(idle), ctypes.byref(kern), ctypes.byref(user))\n        idle_t = idle.dwLow\n        total_t = idle.dwLow + kern.dwLow + user.dwLow\n        if hasattr(get_cpu_win, \"_p\"):\n            d = total_t - get_cpu_win._p[0]\n            p = (idle_t - get_cpu_win._p[1]) / d * 100 if d else 0\n        else:\n            p = 0\n        get_cpu_win._p = (total_t, idle_t)\n        return max(0, round(p, 1))\n    except:\n        return 0\n\n# ── Windows top process (CPU) ──\ndef get_top_cpu_proc():\n    try:\n        import psutil\n        procs = []\n        for p in psutil.process_iter([\"name\", \"cpu_percent\"]):\n            try:\n                n = p.name()\n                c = p.cpu_percent(interval=0.05)\n                if c > 0.5:\n                    procs.append((c, n))\n            except:\n                pass\n        procs.sort(key=lambda x: x[0], reverse=True)\n        if procs:\n            return procs[0][1][:20], procs[0][0]\n    except:\n        pass\n    return \"---\", 0\n\n# ── GPU via pynvml ──\n_gpu_init_ok = False\ndef _init_gpu():\n    global _gpu_init_ok\n    if not _gpu_init_ok:\n        try:\n            import pynvml\n            pynvml.nvmlInit()\n            _gpu_init_ok = True\n        except Exception:\n            _gpu_init_ok = False\n    return _gpu_init_ok\n\ndef get_gpu_info():\n    if not _init_gpu():\n        return None, \"---\"\n    try:\n        import pynvml\n        h = pynvml.nvmlDeviceGetHandleByIndex(0)\n        util = pynvml.nvmlDeviceGetUtilizationRates(h)\n        import subprocess\n        r = subprocess.getoutput('cmd /c nvidia-smi --query-compute-apps=pid,process_name --format=csv,noheader 2>nul')\n        lines = [l.strip() for l in r.strip().splitlines() if l.strip()]\n        names = []\n        for line in lines:\n            parts = line.split(',')\n            if len(parts) >= 2:\n                name = parts[1].strip()\n                if name and name not in ('[Insufficient Permissions]', '[N/A]'):\n                    if '\\\\' in name:\n                        name = name.split('\\\\')[-1]\n                    names.append(name[:20])\n        seen = set()\n        unique = []\n        for n in names:\n            if n.lower() not in seen:\n                seen.add(n.lower())\n                unique.append(n)\n        return int(util.gpu), unique[0] if unique else \"---\"\n    except Exception:\n        return None, \"---\"\n\ndef pct_col(p):\n    return \"#ff2222\" if p >= 90 else \"#ff8800\" if p >= 70 else \"#00ff88\"\n\ndef windows_overlay():\n    import tkinter as tk\n\n    root = tk.Tk()\n    root.overrideredirect(True)\n    root.attributes(\"-topmost\", True)\n    root.configure(bg=\"#111111\")\n\n    mon2_w, mon2_h = 1536, 864\n    W, H = 220, 90\n    x = 1536 + (mon2_w - W) - 20\n    y = 20\n    root.geometry(f\"{W}x{H}+{x}+{y}\")\n\n    def ds(e): root._x, root._y = e.x, e.y\n    def dm(e): root.geometry(f\"+{e.x_root-root._x}+{e.y_root-root._y}\")\n    root.bind(\"<Button-1>\", ds)\n    root.bind(\"<B1-Motion>\", dm)\n\n    font = (\"Consolas\", 14, \"bold\")\n\n    cpu_lbl = tk.Label(root, text=\"CPU : ---%  (---)\", bg=\"#111111\", fg=\"#00ff88\",\n                       font=font, anchor=\"w\", padx=10, pady=3, relief=\"flat\", bd=0)\n    cpu_lbl.pack(fill=\"x\")\n\n    gpu_lbl = tk.Label(root, text=\"GPU : ---%  (---)\", bg=\"#111111\", fg=\"#ff8800\",\n                       font=font, anchor=\"w\", padx=10, pady=3, relief=\"flat\", bd=0)\n    gpu_lbl.pack(fill=\"x\")\n\n    def update():\n        cpu = get_cpu_win()\n        cpu_name, cpu_val = get_top_cpu_proc()\n        gpu, gpu_name = get_gpu_info()\n\n        cpu_lbl.config(text=f\"CPU : {cpu:5.1f}%  ({cpu_name} {cpu_val:.0f}%)\", fg=pct_col(cpu))\n        if gpu is not None:\n            gpu_lbl.config(text=f\"GPU : {gpu:3d}%  ({gpu_name})\", fg=pct_col(gpu))\n        else:\n            gpu_lbl.config(text=\"GPU :  N/A  (---)\", fg=\"#888888\")\n\n        root.after(1000, update)\n\n    root.after(500, update)\n    root.mainloop()\n\ndef terminal_bar():\n    print(\"CPU/GPU monitor (Ctrl+C to exit)\")\n    while True:\n        cpu = get_cpu_win()\n        gpu, gpu_names = get_gpu_info()\n        cpu_name, cpu_val = get_top_cpu_proc()\n        g = f\" GPU {gpu:3d}% ({gpu_names})\" if gpu is not None else \" GPU  N/A\"\n        print(f\"\\r  {time.strftime('%H:%M:%S')}  CPU {cpu:5.1f}% ({cpu_name} {cpu_val:.0f}%){g}     \", end=\"\", flush=True)\n        time.sleep(1)\n\nif __name__ == \"__main__\":\n    if IS_WINDOWS:\n        windows_overlay()\n    else:\n        terminal_bar()\n","path":"/home/apinan/.openclaw/workspace/sysmon.py"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":382,"output":2017,"cacheRea