{"type":"message","id":"f81cd2c7","parentId":"854f4d8b","timestamp":"2026-05-07T16:23:47.074Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The user is saying the CPU% shown in the task bar and the program name displayed don't match. \n\nLooking at the code:\n1. `get_cpu_win()` - uses ctypes to get system CPU usage (overall system CPU)\n2. `get_top_cpu_proc()` - uses psutil to get the process with highest CPU%\n\nSo the CPU% shows total system CPU usage, but the process name shows the top process by CPU. These are two different things and might not be related - the top CPU process might use very little CPU overall.\n\nThe user probably expects the CPU% shown to match the process. But actually they're independent:\n\n\n- System CPU could be high because of many processes, not just the top one\n- The top process name shown might not be the reason for high CPU\n\nThis is actually correct behavior, but the user wants them to match. I could either show the CPU% of the specific top process alongside its name, or display the individual process CPU% instead of total system CPU%. The second approach makes more sense - showing what the top process is actually consuming.\n\nI'll update the display to show the specific process CPU% next to its name, rather than the overall system CPU%. This way the user sees which program is responsible for the resource usage.","thinkingSignature":"79b7b4697e512a78c12a60037a9722543a86b964c8e5322e6030320a3c20c377"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_f0a2gv0bjhvq_1","name":"edit","arguments":{"edits":[{"newText":"        cpu_lbl.config(text=f\"CPU : {cpu_val:.0f}%\", fg=pct_col(cpu_val))\n        cpu_name_lbl.config(text=f\"{cpu_name}\")","oldText":"        cpu_lbl.config(text=f\"CPU : {cpu:5.1f}%\", fg=pct_col(cpu))\n        cpu_name_lbl.config(text=f\"{cpu_name} {cpu_val:.0f}%\")"}],"path":"/home/apinan/.openclaw/workspace/sysmon.py"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage"