{"type":"message","id":"a8ebf4b2","parentId":"c7e63f0a","timestamp":"2026-05-07T16:26:07.581Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now the display is:\n- Line 1: CPU : 12% (overall system CPU usage)\n- Line 2: chrome.exe 605% (chrome using 605% of ONE CORE)\n\nBut there's still a problem — 605% is weird. That means psutil is accumulating across multiple cores. The psutil cpu_percent for a single process can exceed 100% if it uses multiple cores. For comparison with Task Manager (which shows per-core %), we should either cap at 100 or show it differently.\n\nActually, looking at the image - Task Manager shows 12% overall CPU. The overlay shows \"CPU 605%\" which is clearly wrong as a total. \n\nWait, I need to look more carefully at what the user sent. The image description shows the overlay at top right with \"CPU 605%, GPU 5%\" while Task Manager shows \"CPU is 12%\". So my current code is definitely showing the per-process percentage inflated across all cores instead of the system-wide percentage that Task Manager is displaying.\n\nI need to restructure this so the top line shows the overall system CPU usage (the actual 12% from Task Manager), and the second line shows just the top consuming process with its per-process percentage formatted to match what Task Manager displays.","thinkingSignature":"4ed09714e0c3362dedbcb94f68fbef55aec703f567e306844ec509e99445dd3b"},{"type":"text","text":"\n\nเห็นปัญหาแล้วครับเจ้านาย!\n\n- บรรทัดแรก: **overall CPU ทั้งระบบ** → ต้องได้ 12%\n- บรรทัดสอง: **โปรแกรมที่กิน CPU มากสุด** → chrome.exe 605% (ของ core เดียว)\n\nรอสักครู่ครับ 🧑🏼‍💻"}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":193,"output":394,"cacheRead":132320,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":132907,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1778171157021,"responseId":"064bf016ff66fe538ec17a45bcbe3ca9"}}
