{"type":"message","id":"11025321","parentId":"40a86449","timestamp":"2026-05-07T16:29:06.398Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The issue is clear from the code. In `get_cpu_win()`:- Idle time delta = `idle_t - get_cpu_win._p[1]`- Total time delta = `d = total_t - get_cpu_win._p[0]`\n- CPU% = `idle_delta / total_delta * 100`\n\nThis gives the IDLE percentage (time NOT working). So `p = (idle_t - get_cpu_win._p[1]) / d * 100` gives `% of time CPU was idle`. \n\nSo CPU% used = `100 - p`. But the formula I wrote `(idle_t - _p[1]) / d * 100` gives idle%. \n\nWait, let me re-check. \n\nActually, I see it now — `idle_delta / total_delta` gives the fraction of time the CPU was idle, so multiplying by 100 converts that to a percentage. But I need the opposite: I should be dividing the active time (user + kernel deltas) by the total time, not idle time by total time. That's where the bug is.\n\nLet me trace through the logic more carefully. The `total_t` I'm calculating is actually just the sum of user + kernel + idle time — it doesn't include other wait states. So the formula is correct for what's being measured, but I'm computing idle percentage when I want CPU usage percentage. I need to subtract the idle fraction from 100 to get the actual CPU utilization.\n\nWait, let me recalculate this properly. The total delta should be idle + kernel + user deltas combined. If I divide idle delta by total delta, I get the fraction of time spent idle. So CPU usage is 1 minus that fraction, multiplied by 100. But the current code has the formula backwards — it's missing the complement and using the wrong numerator. Now I'm seeing the actual issue—the code is showing 605% because the previous idle value wasn't properly initialized or cached, so the first reading produced a garbage delta. But looking at the screenshot again, the real problem might be that overall CPU is reading 12% as shown in Task Manager, but the overlay is displaying a different value or displaying multiple percentages incorrectly. the per-core total.\n\nLet me trace through the CPU calculation with psutil to verify whether it's actually summing per-core percentages or if there's something else going on with how the idle time is being computed.\n","thinkingSignature":"5db35c6ea9bca91408ecb6c496f23a086c2688ab9955cfcc97a1c36af5bf3cbd"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_mxfq3mmm75b9_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"\"/mnt/c/Windows/System32/WindowsPowerShell/v1.0/powershell.exe\" -Command \"\n\\$py = 'C:\\Users\\Apinan\\AppData\\Local\\Programs\\Python\\Python312\\python.exe'\n\\$tmp = \\\"\\$env:TEMP\\\\cputest.py\\\"\n@'\nimport ctypes, time\n\nclass FT(ctypes.Structure):\n    _fields_ = [('dwLow', ctypes.c_ulong), ('dwHigh', ctypes.c_ulong)]\n\nk = ctypes.windll.kernel32\nidle1, kern1, user1 = FT(), FT(), FT()\nk.GetSystemTimes(ctypes.byref(idle1), ctypes.byref(kern1), ctypes.byref(user1))\ntime.sleep(1)\nidle2, kern2, user2 = FT(), FT(), FT()\nk.GetSystemTimes(ctypes.byref(idle2), ctypes.byref(kern2), ctypes.byref(user2))\n\nidle_d = idle2.dwLow - idle1.dwLow\nkern_d = kern2.dwLow - kern1.dwLow\nuser_d = user2.dwLow - user1.dwLow\ntotal_d = idle_d + kern_d + user_d\n\npct = (kern_d + user_d) / total_d * 100\nprint('total_d:', total_d, 'idle:', idle_d, 'kern:', kern_d, 'user:', user_d)\nprint('CPU%:', round(pct, 1))\n'@ | Out-File -FilePath \\$tmp -Encoding utf8\n& \\$py \\$tmp\n\" 2>&1"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":354,"output":856,"cacheRead":133216,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":134426,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1778171330375,"responseId":"064bf0c3453269df2cb0bc950ab0671f"}}
