{"type":"message","id":"303eb11b","parentId":"cd2a56c8","timestamp":"2026-05-07T16:30:10.857Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Wait - psutil.cpu_percent(interval=0) returns instantaneous per-CPU (e.g. 8 cores = can go up to 800%). But we want system-wide %.\n\nActually looking at psutil docs again:\n- `cpu_percent(interval=None)` → instantaneous (per-core can exceed 100%)\n- `cpu_percent(interval=1)` → system-wide over 1 second (0-100%)\n\nThe image shows Task Manager 12% CPU overall. Let me use interval=1 but cache the result so we don't block for 1 second each update.\n\n\nThe real problem is the calculation in get_cpu_win was wrong - it was dividing by total delta instead of working time delta. Using interval=1 directly gives the correct system-wide percentage, though it means waiting each update. If I call it with interval=None first and then again with interval=1, I should get accurate results without blocking on the first call.\n","thinkingSignature":"50a74ee56a7a0b7aa39010e6e83b7f5ed3d570f2bc5027debb794e57bb5360a4"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_onxqpdk8o89y_1","name":"edit","arguments":{"edits":[{"newText":"_cpu_cache = None\ndef get_cpu_win():\n    global _cpu_cache\n    try:\n        import psutil\n        if _cpu_cache is None:\n            # first call: initialize, wait 1s\n            _cpu_cache = psutil.cpu_percent(interval=1)\n            return round(_cpu_cache, 1)\n        else:\n            # subsequent: use cached value + get fresh\n            prev = _cpu_cache\n            _cpu_cache = psutil.cpu_percent(interval=1)\n            return round(_cpu_cache, 1)\n    except:\n        return 0","oldText":"_prev_cpu = None\ndef get_cpu_win():\n    global _prev_cpu\n    try:\n        import psutil\n        c = psutil.cpu_percent(interval=0)\n        if _prev_cpu is not None:\n            diff = c - _prev_cpu\n            # normalize: psutil returns per-core, cap at 100\n            pct = min(max(diff, 0), 