{"type":"message","id":"acd1d3f5","parentId":"375a55ef","timestamp":"2026-05-07T16:32:02.054Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The image shows:\n- Task Manager: CPU 12%, GPU 0%, RAM 48%\n- Overlay: CPU 13% (System Idle Process 397%), GPU 0% (explorer.exe)\n\nSo the CPU overall is correct (13% vs Task Manager 12%) - close enough! \n\nBut the GPU name is showing \"explorer.exe\" instead of \"---\" (when GPU is 0%). The issue is that `nvidia-smi --query-compute-apps` still returns processes even when GPU usage is 0% - it shows any process that has a GPU context, including explorer.exe which probably has a small GPU footprint.\n\n\nI'm checking why explorer.exe appears as a GPU process - it likely has a GPU context open even though it's not actively using the GPU, so I need to either filter by actual GPU memory usage or just exclude explorer.exe since it shouldn't be counted as a real GPU consumer.\n","thinkingSignature":"51fe3783e520459c5fcb50d59db05e1796dead5593a60ef4d896b30ca416a999"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_7odvtfew2s9v_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"\"/mnt/c/Windows/System32/cmd.exe\" /c \"cd C:\\ & nvidia-smi --query-compute-apps=pid,process_name,used_memory --format=csv,noheader\" 2>&1 | head -10"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":138,"output":264,"cacheRead":136832,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":137234,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1778171515017,"responseId":"064bf17e433200ab4e666f2af7d3259f"}}
