{"type":"message","id":"ff818919","parentId":"0ff85d3c","timestamp":"2026-05-07T16:32:12.875Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"I see the issue now! The nvidia-smi query returns processes with `[Insufficient Permissions]` and `[N/A]` memory, which means the GPU processes can't be queried. So `get_gpu_info()` returns `unique[0]` which is the FIRST process from nvidia-smi, which is explorer.exe (with the full path `[Insufficient Permissions]`).\n\nBut wait, explorer.exe was being shown as GPU program name... that's because:\n1. The first process in the list is `2236, [Insufficient Permissions], [N/A]`\n2. The second is `5808, C:\\Windows\\explorer.exe, [N/A]`\n\n\n3. My code filters out `name not in ('[Insufficient Permissions]', '[N/A]')` but not `[Insufficient Permissions]` which appears as the NAME, not memory. So the first entry has `[Insufficient Permissions]` as the process name, not as a separator, which means it should be getting filtered out, but explorer.exe is still showing up because it's in the second entry with a valid name and valid memory value.\n\nThe filtering logic has a gap — it removes entries where the name field itself is `[Insufficient Permissions]` or `[N/A]`, but it's missing the case where the name field is actually a valid path like `C:\\Windows\\explorer.exe`. Since explorer.exe is appearing with valid memory allocation, it's slipping through the filter and being returned as the top process, which doesn't make sense for GPU usage. I need to either check if the memory field is `[N/A]` or implement a minimum memory threshold to filter out processes that appear valid but aren't actually using GPU resources.","thinkingSignature":"9612e305d8aeaf64ec289ccbb614188714123cbc2d36d1c24fa050c8e27fd2fc"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_hwt41771sp8j_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"\"/mnt/c/Windows/System32/cmd.exe\" /c \"cd C:\\ & nvidia-smi --query-compute-apps=pid,process_name,used_memory --format