{"type":"message","id":"446b82e3","parentId":"8beb7f39","timestamp":"2026-05-07T16:36:20.471Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The issue is psutil.cpu_percent(interval=None) returns the CPU % since the last call. So on the first call after a fresh start, it returns the % since boot. Subsequent calls return % since last call. But when we call every second, we get the right delta. The problem is after `pct = max(0.0, min(100.0, diff))` we cap at 100.\n\nBut wait - if the user has 24 cores, and System Idle Process = 582%, that's 582% on some core(s). This means the CPU cores are NOT all equal - some are fully idle, some are at 100%. So the overall % is (total busy time) / (total time across all cores). \n\nIf SIP uses 582% across cores, the overall % = (582% / num_cores * 100). If num_cores is 24, that's 582/24 ≈ 24%.\n\nSo the overall % should show ≈ 24%, not 57%. But Task Manager shows 57%...\n\nMaybe I'm misinterpreting the image. Could be that SIP at 582% is being calculated differently, or perhaps the overall percentage includes something else I'm not accounting for.\n\nThe simplest explanation: psutil returns an average across all cores (0-100%), while the per-process percentage can exceed 100% when a process spans multiple cores. Task Manager's per-process list shows the process CPU%, which for SIP equals the combined core usage. So if SIP shows 582%, that's the total across all cores, not the average.\n","thinkingSignature":"2f3704b77638f88eb5a5b8ee0cc7ab2de64570334d01da5a4185b2aa1317379e"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_nl1zsej6qj58_1","name":"edit","arguments":{"edits":[{"newText":"        cpu_lbl.config(text=f\"CPU : {cpu:.0f}%\", fg=pct_col(cpu))\n        cpu_name_lbl.config(text=f\"{cpu_name}\")","oldText":"        cpu_lbl.config(text=f\"CPU : {cpu:.0f}%\", fg=pct_col(cpu))\n        cpu_name_lbl.config(text=f\"{cpu_name} {cpu_val:.0f}%\")"}],"path":"/home/apinan/.openclaw/workspace/sysmon.py"}}],"api":"anthro