{"type":"message","id":"7ef62640","parentId":"a65c9c30","timestamp":"2026-05-07T16:37:44.493Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Good. But there's still the issue - `psutil.cpu_percent(interval=1)` blocks for 1 second. The update loop is every 1 second too. But that's the only reliable way.\n\nAlso, now the CPU shows without the %. Let me think more carefully:\n\nThe problem is `psutil.cpu_percent(interval=1)` blocks 1 second, and during that second, the update loop pauses. But the loop calls `root.after(1000, update)` which is ~1s. So there should be roughly 1s between calls. Should be OK.\n\nWait - but Task Manager shows 57% while overlay shows 12%. \n\nThat's still wrong. Hmm, let me trace through the update loop timing more carefully. The initial update runs at 500ms with a stale CPU value, then subsequent updates run every 1000ms. So if I call `psutil.cpu_percent(interval=1)` at time T, it blocks until T+1, then the next `root.after(1000, update)` fires at T+1.5, which calls `psutil.cpu_percent(interval=1)` again and blocks until T+2. That means I'm getting readings spaced about 1.5 seconds apart, not 1 second. That timing mismatch might explain the discrepancy with Task Manager.\n\nActually, if the loop was already running and had cached values from before, the first call after a restart would show the previous cached value—which was stale and low at 12%. The user needs to wait for a fresh reading now.\n\nLet me verify the approach: Task Manager shows 57% overall, and `psutil.cpu_percent(interval=1)` should match that since it measures the system-wide CPU usage over 1 second.\n\nI think the real issue is that I'm returning a cached value from the first blocking call on initial load, which is stale. The subsequent calls should be correct, but there's a ~500ms delay before the first reading updates, so the user sees the old cached value initially.\n\nLooking at Task Manager showing 57% while my script shows 12% — that's a huge discrepancy that doesn't match the expected measurement window. Something might be off with how the interval is being handled across multiple calls.\n\nIf the system was at 12% during the first measurement and Task Manager switched to 57% after, that would explain the difference, but it's unlikely both happened at the exact same moment. The most probable explanation is that `psutil.cpu_percent(interval=1)` was giving stale cached values on the first few calls before warming up.\n\nI'm thinking the core issue is that psutil caches the first reading, so the second reading might be capturing CPU during the second-second while the overlay was already showing something else. The simplest solution is to ensure each `get_cpu_win()` call blocks for a full second to get a fresh measurement, with a separate thread handling the caching to keep the UI responsive. Looking at the update loop, the first call at 500ms uses a cached value while subsequent calls at 1000ms and 2000ms should both block and wait for their measurements. The issue might be that `psutil.cpu_percent()` with an interval is returning cached data on the first call, so I should test calling it with `interval=None` to force an immediate reading instead.\n\nLet me try using a background thread to read CPU values continuously without blocking the UI, storing results in a queue that the main loop can pull from.","thinkingSignature":"a09157735d7723705fcf810b8fe88e7cf84a11ea016e838eb3d1c4d5d37561f0"},{"type":"text","text":"\n\n\n🧑🏼‍💻 ยังไม่ตรงอยู่ดี\n\nปัญหา: `psutil.cpu_percent(interval=1)` มัน cache ค่าแรก + block 1 วินาที ทุกครั้ง → ค่าค้าง\n\n**วิธีแก้:** ใช้ thread อ่าน CPU พร้อมกัน background ไม่บล็อก UI\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_e4no9ox9bz8s_1","name":"write","arguments":{"content":"#!/usr/bin/env python3\n\"\"\"Floating CPU/GPU monitor — always-on-top overlay.\"\"\"\nimport sys, os, time, threading, queue\n\nIS_WINDOWS = os.name == \"nt\"\n\n# ── CPU reader thread — blocks 1s per reading, never stale ──\n_q = queue.Queue()\ndef _reader():\n    import psutil\n    while True:\n        _q.put(psutil.cpu_percent(interval=1))\n_cpu_thread = threading.Thread(target=_reader, daemon=True)\n\n# ── Windows CPU (fresh per-second, from background thread) ──\ndef get_cpu_win():\n    try:\n        # drain queue if available (newest reading)\n        while True:\n            try: v = _q.get_nowait()\n            except queue.Empty: break\n        if v is not None:\n            return round(v, 1)\n    except:\n        pass\n    return 0\n\n# ── Windows top process (CPU) ──\ndef get_top_cpu_proc():\n    try:\n        import psutil\n        procs = []\n        for p in psutil.process_iter([\"name\", \"cpu_percent\"]):\n            try:\n                c = p.cpu_percent(interval=0.1)\n                if c > 0.5:\n                    procs.append((c, p.name()))\n            except:\n                pass\n        procs.sort(key=lambda x: x[0], reverse=True)\n        if procs:\n            return procs[0][1][:20], procs[0][0]\n    except:\n        pass\n    return \"---\", 0\n\n# ── GPU via pynvml ──\n_gpu_init_ok = False\ndef _init_gpu():\n    global _gpu_init_ok\n    if not _gpu_init_ok:\n        try:\n            import pynvml\n            pynvml.nvmlInit()\n            _gpu_init_ok = True\n        except Exception:\n            _gpu_init_ok = False\n    return _gpu_init_ok\n\ndef get_gpu_info():\n    if not _init_gpu():\n        return None, \"---\"\n    try:\n        import pynvml\n        h = pynvml.nvmlDeviceGetHandleByIndex(0)\n        util = pynvml.nvmlDeviceGetUtilizationRates(h)\n        import subprocess\n        r = subprocess.getoutput(\n            'cmd /c nvidia-smi --query-compute-apps=pid,process_name,used_memory --format=csv,noheader 2>nul'\n        )\n        lines = [l.strip() for l in r.strip().splitlines() if l.strip()]\n        named = []\n        for line in lines:\n            parts = line.split(',')\n            if len(parts) < 3:\n                continue\n            name = parts[1].strip()\n            mem_str = parts[2].strip()\n            if not name or name in ('[Insufficient Permissions]', '[N/A]'):\n                continue\n            if mem_str in ('[N/A]', '0'):\n                continue\n            if '\\\\' in name:\n                name = name.split('\\\\')[-1]\n            mem_val = 0\n            try:\n                if 'MiB' in mem_str:\n                    mem_val = int(mem_str.split()[0])\n                elif 'GiB' in mem_str:\n                    mem_val = int(float(mem_str.split()[0]) * 1024)\n            except:\n                pass\n            named.append((mem_val, name[:20]))\n        named.sort(key=lambda x: x[0], reverse=True)\n        seen = set()\n        unique = []\n        for m, n in named:\n            if m > 0 and n.lower() not in seen:\n                seen.add(n.lower())\n                unique.append(n)\n        return int(util.gpu), unique[0] if unique else \"---\"\n    except Exception:\n        return None, \"---\"\n\ndef pct_col(p):\n    return \"#ff2222\" if p >= 90 else \"#ff8800\" if p >= 70 else \"#00ff88\"\n\ndef windows_overlay():\n    import tkinter as tk\n\n    root = tk.Tk()\n    root.overrideredirect(True)\n    root.attributes(\"-topmost\", True)\n    root.configure(bg=\"#111111\")\n\n    mon2_w, mon2_h = 1536, 864\n    W, H = 260, 130\n    x = 1536 + (mon2_w - W) - 20\n    y = 20\n    root.geometry(f\"{W}x{H}+{x}+{y}\")\n\n    def ds(e): root._x, root._y = e.x, e.y\n    def dm(e): root.geometry(f\"+{e.x_root-root._x}+{e.y_root-root._y}\")\n    root.bind(\"<Button-1>\", ds)\n    root.bind(\"<B1-Motion>\", dm)\n\n    font = (\"Consolas\", 16, \"bold\")\n    sub = (\"Consolas\", 12)\n\n    cpu_lbl = tk.Label(root, text=\"CPU : ---%\", bg=\"#111111\", fg=\"#00ff88\",\n                       font=font, anchor=\"w\", padx=10, pady=3, relief=\"flat\", bd=0)\n    cpu_lbl.pack(fill=\"x\")\n\n    cpu_name_lbl = tk.Label(root, text=\"---\", bg=\"#111111\", fg=\"#00ccff\",\n                             font=sub, anchor=\"w\", padx=10, pady=3, relief=\"flat\", bd=0)\n    cpu_name_lbl.pack(fill=\"x\")\n\n    gpu_lbl = tk.Label(root, text=\"GPU : ---%\", bg=\"#111111\", fg=\"#ff8800\",\n                       font=font, anchor=\"w\", padx=10, pady=3, relief=\"flat\", bd=0)\n    gpu_lbl.pack(fill=\"x\")\n\n    gpu_name_lbl = tk.Label(root, text=\"---\", bg=\"#111111\", fg=\"#ff8800\",\n                              font=sub, anchor=\"w\", padx=10, pady=3, relief=\"flat\", bd=0)\n    gpu_name_lbl.pack(fill=\"x\")\n\n    def update():\n        cpu = get_cpu_win()\n        cpu_name, _ = get_top_cpu_proc()\n        gpu, gpu_name = get_gpu_info()\n\n        cpu_lbl.config(text=f\"CPU : {cpu:.0f}%\", fg=pct_col(cpu))\n        cpu_name_lbl.config(text=f\"{cpu_name}\")\n        if gpu is not None:\n            gpu_lbl.config(text=f\"GPU : {gpu:.0f}%\", fg=pct_col(gpu))\n            gpu_name_lbl.config(text=f\"{gpu_name}\")\n        else:\n            gpu_lbl.config(text=\"GPU :  N/A\", fg=\"#888888\")\n            gpu_name_lbl.config(text=\"\")\n\n        root.after(1000, update)\n\n    root.after(500, update)\n    root.mainloop()\n\ndef main():\n    global _cpu_thread\n    _cpu_thread.start()\n    if IS_WINDOWS:\n        windows_overlay()\n    else:\n        terminal_bar()\n\nif __name__ == \"__main__\":\n    main()\n","path":"/home/apinan/.openclaw/workspace/sysmon.py"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":200,"output":2372,"cacheRead":143104,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":145676,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1778171826387,"responseId":"064bf2b5b0ff0be7468ee93275f6b5a6"}}
