{"type":"message","id":"b9b4a94f","parentId":"9c501551","timestamp":"2026-05-07T16:44:17.478Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Task Manager shows 33%, overlay shows 16%. Still off.\n\nThe issue: psutil.cpu_percent(interval=1) and Task Manager's per-core summing might diverge. \n\nTask Manager likely shows total CPU% as an average across all CPU cores over a period. psutil.cpu_percent(interval=1) should give the same.\n\nBut wait - the task manager is showing 33% (3/4 cores roughly), and our reading is 16%. The discrepancy might be because:\n\n1. The reader thread starts AFTER the main thread starts\n2. The first reading in the queue might not be the right one\n\nWait - actually the queue might have OLD readings. \n\nI'm checking the queue drain logic in the update function. When the queue is empty, get_nowait throws an Empty exception, and I'm returning 0. But if there's a stale value in there, we'd be reading old data instead of current readings.\n\nActually, the real issue might be with how the reader thread works - it blocks for 1 second on the first call to get the initial CPU percentage, then puts results in the queue at intervals. The main thread should get fresh readings, but there could be a timing issue where we're grabbing an outdated value instead of waiting for a fresh one. I'm draining stale readings from the queue in get_cpu_win and returning the most recent one, so that should be fine. But I need to reconsider how Task Manager actually calculates CPU percentage — it might be averaging across all cores differently than I'm accounting for.\n\nOn a 4-core system, if the total CPU usage is 33%, that could mean one core at 100% and three cores at 10% each (which gives about 32.5%), not 132% total. The System Idle Process showing 582% makes sense since it can sum across cores, but Task Manager's displayed percentage is normalized to 100%, so I need to check how psutil actually reports this versus what Task Manager shows. I'm realizing Task Manager probably displays the overall CPU usage (around 33%) while our overlay shows 16%, which suggests there might be a timing or calculation difference. Rather than keep tweaking psutil settings, I should just add a config option that lets users set a manual offset to match Task Manager's reading, or I need to dig deeper into how the reader thread is actually feeding data to the queue and whether the drain logic is working correctly. I see the issue now - Task Manager is showing 33% which makes sense as an average across all cores, while our reader is getting 16%, so there's a real discrepancy I need to investigate. Rather than keep digging into the implementation details, I should just accept that for the user's purposes, having the overlay display track Task Manager is what matters, and the current approach might just need adjustment rather than a complete overhaul.\n\nLooking at the timing more carefully: the reader thread blocks for 1 second on the first iteration, so during that initial window our cached value is 0 and we return early. Then after that first reading completes and goes into the queue, we're returning the right value for about a second before the next update cycle triggers another blocking call. The real problem seems to be that 33% vs 16% gap, which suggests the reader might not be capturing the same CPU metrics Task Manager is using. I think the real issue is that the reader thread blocks for a full second during initialization, and while it's waiting, the main thread keeps returning stale cached values from earlier in the loop. So the timing of when we fetch new data versus when we drain the queue matters more than I initially thought.\n\nA cleaner approach would be to remove the reader thread entirely and instead do a non-blocking 1-second read right in the update function itself, so we're always getting fresh data without the blocking overhead.\n\nActually, that won't work either since tkinter can't handle the blocking delay. I need a proper background thread approach where the worker continuously fetches CPU data every second and the main loop just retrieves whatever's been buffered in the queue.\n\nThe drain logic checks if the queue is empty and returns None, otherwise it pulls the latest value and resets the counter. But I'm realizing the first reading from psutil.cpu_percent might be 0 since it compares against a zeroed counter initially, which would explain the discrepancy with Task Manager showing different values. the reader thread blocks for 1 second during initialization, so the first value in the queue after startup might not reflect the true CPU load yet, causing subsequent readings to be artificially low. a fresh reading immediately instead of waiting a full second, since we already have the idle process info from the initial read. Let me refactor to remove the caching logic and just read fresh values each time.","thinkingSignature":"b30831cdf25d1081c6f4bcb1e933aa95ad3bb020d9365555ec8e94093efacd27"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_gfp0xb2zyslp_1","name":"edit","arguments":{"edits":[{"newText":"        while True:\n            try: v = _q.get_nowait(); break\n            except queue.Empty:\n                import time as _time; _time.sleep(0.05)\n        return round(v, 1) if v is not None else 0","oldText":"        while True:\n            try: v = _q.get_nowait()\n            except queue.Empty: break\n        if v is not None:\n            return round(v, 1)\n    except:\n        pass\n    return 0"}],"path":"/home/apinan/.openclaw/workspace/sysmon.py"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":145447,"output":1125,"cacheRead":96,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":146668,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1778172221216,"responseId":"064bf440699e748c037512e3feb49936"}}
{"type":"message","id":"896c57d9","parentId":"b9b4a94f","timestamp":"2026-05-07T16:44:17.548Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_gfp0xb2zyslp_1","toolName":"edit","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Successfully replaced 1 block(s) in /home/apinan/.openclaw/workspace/sysmon.py."}],"details":{"diff":"     ...\n  16 def get_cpu_win():\n  17     try:\n  18         # drain queue if available (newest reading)\n  19         while True:\n- 20             try: v = _q.get_nowait()\n- 21             except queue.Empty: break\n- 22         if v is not None:\n- 23             return round(v, 1)\n- 24     except:\n- 25         pass\n- 26     return 0\n+ 20             try: v = _q.get_nowait(); break\n+ 21             except queue.Empty:\n+ 22                 import time as _time; _time.sleep(0.05)\n+ 23         return round(v, 1) if v is not None else 0\n  27 \n  28 # ── Windows top process (CPU) ──\n  29 def get_top_cpu_proc():\n  30     try:\n     ...","firstChangedLine":20},"isError":false,"timestamp":1778172257548}}
{"type":"message","id":"c40040b5","parentId":"896c57d9","timestamp":"2026-05-07T16:44:43.018Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Wait, this approach has a problem - if the queue is empty and we sleep 0.05s, we might loop many times. And actually, if the queue is empty because the thread just started and hasn't produced a reading yet, we should block briefly.\n\nAlso, the bigger issue: the thread puts a value, then waits 1s, then puts again. But the queue might have old stale values. We need to drain and keep only the latest.\n\nActually the real problem is more fundamental: psutil.cpu_percent(interval=1) with no interval parameter (or None) returns the CPU % since the last call. With interval=1, it blocks for 1 second and returns the CPU % over that 1 second window.\n \nSo every 1 second the thread puts a fresh reading into the queue, and when the main thread calls get_cpu_win(), it drains the queue to get that latest value. If the queue is empty on first call, we'd block for 1 second waiting for the thread to produce something.\n\nThe problem is that if the thread hasn't had time to put anything yet (it needs 1 second to do its first measurement), get_cpu_win() returns 0 on the first call. And if we call it frequently, the values might be stale from the previous reading.\n\nActually wait - the real issue is that `psutil.cpu_percent(interval=None)` returns the CPU percent since the last call, which means each call depends on the previous one. This is fundamentally broken if the main thread reads multiple times faster than the reader thread produces values.\n\nI need to redesign this: the reader thread should block for 1 second to get the actual CPU usage, then immediately put that value in the queue and start waiting for the next 1-second interval. The main thread should just grab whatever's in the queue, or return the last known value if it's recent enough. This way there's no timing ambiguity - the queue always has either a fresh reading or the previous one.","thinkingSignature":"387e3c839da331914eb504d813fb0f711d3bbdc7644fe28203101351fb2d96f4"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_6fkeymnd8ytv_1","name":"write","arguments":{"content":"#!/usr/bin/env python3\n\"\"\"Floating CPU/GPU monitor — always-on-top overlay.\"\"\"\nimport sys, os, time, threading, queue\n\nIS_WINDOWS = os.name == \"nt\"\n\n# ── CPU reader thread: fresh 1s reading every iteration ──\n_q = queue.Queue()\ndef _reader():\n    import psutil\n    while True:\n        # blocks exactly 1s → gives accurate system-wide %\n        _q.put(psutil.cpu_percent(interval=1))\n\n_cpu_started = False\ndef _ensure_cpu_thread():\n    global _cpu_started\n    if not _cpu_started:\n        t = threading.Thread(target=_reader, daemon=True)\n        t.start()\n        _cpu_started = True\n\n# ── Windows CPU ──\ndef get_cpu_win():\n    _ensure_cpu_thread()\n    try:\n        # drain all stale reads, keep only the latest\n        latest = None\n        while True:\n            try: latest = _q.get_nowait()\n            except queue.Empty: break\n        if latest is not None:\n            return round(latest, 1)\n    except:\n        pass\n    return 0\n\n# ── Windows top process (CPU) ──\ndef get_top_cpu_proc():\n    try:\n        import psutil\n        procs = []\n        for p in psutil.process_iter([\"name\", \"cpu_percent\"]):\n            try:\n                c = p.cpu_percent(interval=0.1)\n                if c > 0.5:\n                    procs.append((c, p.name()))\n            except:\n                pass\n        procs.sort(key=lambda x: x[0], reverse=True)\n        if procs:\n            return procs[0][1][:20], procs[0][0]\n    except:\n        pass\n    return \"---\", 0\n\n# ── GPU via pynvml ──\n_gpu_init_ok = False\ndef _init_gpu():\n    global _gpu_init_ok\n    if not _gpu_init_ok:\n        try:\n            import pynvml\n            pynvml.nvmlInit()\n            _gpu_init_ok = True\n        except Exception:\n            _gpu_init_ok = False\n    return _gpu_init_ok\n\ndef get_gpu_info():\n    if not _init_gpu():\n        return None, \"---\"\n    try:\n        import pynvml\n        h = pynvml.nvmlDeviceGetHandleByIndex(0)\n        util = pynvml.nvmlDeviceGetUtilizationRates(h)\n        import subprocess\n        r = subprocess.getoutput(\n            'cmd /c nvidia-smi --query-compute-apps=pid,process_name,used_memory --format=csv,noheader 2>nul'\n        )\n        lines = [l.strip() for l in r.strip().splitlines() if l.strip()]\n        named = []\n        for line in lines:\n            parts = line.split(',')\n            if len(parts) < 3:\n                continue\n            name = parts[1].strip()\n            mem_str = parts[2].strip()\n            if not name or name in ('[Insufficient Permissions]', '[N/A]'):\n                continue\n            if mem_str in ('[N/A]', '0'):\n                continue\n            if '\\\\' in name:\n                name = name.split('\\\\')[-1]\n            mem_val = 0\n            try:\n                if 'MiB' in mem_str:\n                    mem_val = int(mem_str.split()[0])\n                elif 'GiB' in mem_str:\n                    mem_val = int(float(mem_str.split()[0]) * 1024)\n            except:\n                pass\n            named.append((mem_val, name[:20]))\n        named.sort(key=lambda x: x[0], reverse=True)\n        seen = set()\n        unique = []\n        for m, n in named:\n            if m > 0 and n.lower() not in seen:\n                seen.add(n.lower())\n                unique.append(n)\n        return int(util.gpu), unique[0] if unique else \"---\"\n    except Exception:\n        return None, \"---\"\n\ndef pct_col(p):\n    return \"#ff2222\" if p >= 90 else \"#ff8800\" if p >= 70 else \"#00ff88\"\n\ndef windows_overlay():\n    import tkinter as tk\n\n    root = tk.Tk()\n    root.overrideredirect(True)\n    root.attributes(\"-topmost\", True)\n    root.configure(bg=\"#111111\")\n\n    mon2_w, mon2_h = 1536, 864\n    W, H = 260, 130\n    x = 1536 + (mon2_w - W) - 20\n    y = 20\n    root.geometry(f\"{W}x{H}+{x}+{y}\")\n\n    def ds(e): root._x, root._y = e.x, e.y\n    def dm(e): root.geometry(f\"+{e.x_root-root._x}+{e.y_root-root._y}\")\n    root.bind(\"<Button-1>\", ds)\n    root.bind(\"<B1-Motion>\", dm)\n\n    font = (\"Consolas\", 16, \"bold\")\n    sub = (\"Consolas\", 12)\n\n    cpu_lbl = tk.Label(root, text=\"CPU : ---%\", bg=\"#111111\", fg=\"#00ff88\",\n                       font=font, anchor=\"w\", padx=10, pady=3, relief=\"flat\", bd=0)\n    cpu_lbl.pack(fill=\"x\")\n\n    cpu_name_lbl = tk.Label(root, text=\"---\", bg=\"#111111\", fg=\"#00ccff\",\n                             font=sub, anchor=\"w\", padx=10, pady=3, relief=\"flat\", bd=0)\n    cpu_name_lbl.pack(fill=\"x\")\n\n    gpu_lbl = tk.Label(root, text=\"GPU : ---%\", bg=\"#111111\", fg=\"#ff8800\",\n                       font=font, anchor=\"w\", padx=10, pady=3, relief=\"flat\", bd=0)\n    gpu_lbl.pack(fill=\"x\")\n\n    gpu_name_lbl = tk.Label(root, text=\"---\", bg=\"#111111\", fg=\"#ff8800\",\n                              font=sub, anchor=\"w\", padx=10, pady=3, relief=\"flat\", bd=0)\n    gpu_name_lbl.pack(fill=\"x\")\n\n    def update():\n        cpu = get_cpu_win()\n        cpu_name, _ = get_top_cpu_proc()\n        gpu, gpu_name = get_gpu_info()\n\n        cpu_lbl.config(text=f\"CPU : {cpu:.0f}%\", fg=pct_col(cpu))\n        cpu_name_lbl.config(text=f\"{cpu_name}\")\n        if gpu is not None:\n            gpu_lbl.config(text=f\"GPU : {gpu:.0f}%\", fg=pct_col(gpu))\n            gpu_name_lbl.config(text=f\"{gpu_name}\")\n        else:\n            gpu_lbl.config(text=\"GPU :  N/A\", fg=\"#888888\")\n            gpu_name_lbl.config(text=\"\")\n\n        root.after(1000, update)\n\n    root.after(500, update)\n    root.mainloop()\n\nif __name__ == \"__main__\":\n    if IS_WINDOWS:\n        windows_overlay()\n    else:\n        print(\"CPU/GPU monitor (Ctrl+C to exit)\")\n        while True:\n            cpu = get_cpu_win()\n            gpu, gn = get_gpu_info()\n            cpu_name, _ = get_top_cpu_proc()\n            g = f\" GPU {gpu:.0f}% ({gn})\" if gpu is not None else \" GPU  N/A\"\n            print(f\"\\r  {time.strftime('%H:%M:%S')}  CPU {cpu:.0f}% ({cpu_name}){g}     \", end=\"\", flush=True)\n            time.sleep(1)\n","path":"/home/apinan/.openclaw/workspace/sysmon.py"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":207,"output":2087,"cacheRead":145536,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":147830,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1778172257556,"responseId":"064bf463d9a0099f15c8cb6f597effed"}}
