{"type":"message","id":"15268d83","parentId":"28034eea","timestamp":"2026-05-07T16:44:50.167Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Good. Now the logic is clean:1. Reader thread puts `psutil.cpu_percent(interval=1)` every iteration (blocks exactly 1s)\n2. Main thread drains the queue on every update() call (every 1s)\n3. `get_cpu_win()` returns the latest reading from the queue\n\nThis means every 1 second, the main thread gets a fresh reading from the queue. The queue should always have at most 1 item waiting (since we drain and then wait 1s).\n\nBut I'm still worried about the timing. The first reading takes 1s to get. Then after 1s, the thread puts another. But the tkinter `after(1000, update)` fires every 1s. \n\nSo if there's a timing mismatch, the queue could grow unbounded as readings pile up faster than we drain them. The drain-to-latest approach should help with responsiveness, but I need to make sure we're actually draining the queue completely each time.\n","thinkingSignature":"e60cc00c94db1ca7430e6e6086da6738fe0186b75a110ea594cba495cabebeca"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_j30vt2e6wxn9_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"cp /home/apinan/.openclaw/workspace/sysmon.py /mnt/c/Users/Apinan/Desktop/SysMon/sysmon.py\n\n\"/mnt/c/Windows/System32/WindowsPowerShell/v1.0/powershell.exe\" -Command \"\nGet-Process pythonw -EA SilentlyContinue | Stop-Process -Force\nStart-Sleep 1\n\\$proc = Start-Process 'C:\\Users\\Apinan\\AppData\\Local\\Programs\\Python\\Python312\\pythonw.exe' -ArgumentList 'C:\\Users\\Apinan\\Desktop\\SysMon\\sysmon.py' -PassThru\nWrite-Host 'pid:' \\$proc.Id\n\" 2>&1"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":1730,"output":368,"cacheRead":145728,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":147826,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1778172283042,"responseId":"064bf47ccac5b1239e0d12ee3cd3ba98"}}
