{"type":"message","id":"52ef04a9","parentId":"1c2af732","timestamp":"2026-05-07T16:45:10.007Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now, the issue was that the drain was too fast. The problem was that the queue had already accumulated multiple readings by the time we drain it (since the thread reads every 1s and the main loop calls every 1s too). But our drain loop is instant - we drain ALL items at once. That means if there's a gap, we just get the oldest value.\n\nActually no - we want the LATEST. But when we keep reassigning latest, we'd get the most recent.\n\nWait let me think again. The thread puts a value every 1 second. The main loop drains the queue (get_nowait in a while loop). Since it's a FIFO queue, the first item we get is the oldest. The LAST item we get before queue.Empty is the latest.\n \nI see it now - the first item we drain is the oldest, and subsequent iterations pull newer values, so the final assignment before the queue empties gives us the most recent reading. That should be working correctly.\n\nLet me trace through the timing: the thread blocks for 1 second on its first read, then returns that value and immediately blocks again for the next 1-second interval. So if the main thread reads at different offsets within each cycle, we might be getting readings from different points in the averaging window.\n\nActually, I think I've been overcomplicating this. The psutil documentation is clear - without an interval, it returns the CPU usage since the last call, and with interval=1 it blocks for a full second to measure over that 1-second window. So each call in the reader thread is measuring a complete 1-second slice, and as long as we're getting the latest reading, the timing offset shouldn't matter for accuracy.\n\nThe drain loop should be working as intended too - since we're looping until the queue is empty and keeping only the last value, we always get the most recent measurement. But looking at the specific cases the user mentioned (16% vs 33% and 12% vs 57%), the numbers are consistently off by roughly a factor of 2, which suggests something systematic might be wrong with how we're sampling or calculating the percentages.\n\nTask Manager shows CPU usage per core as a total, so if you're at 33% total CPU usage, that means one core is fully saturated or three cores are at 11% each - it's the aggregate across all cores. With 16 cores available, reaching 33% overall would require about 5-6 cores at 100%. So the discrepancy could be that psutil is returning a different metric than what Task Manager displays, or we're not correctly interpreting how the cores contribute to the total percentage.\n\nI think the real issue is that our drain timing creates a race condition where we might be reading from the same measurement interval twice instead of getting fresh data each time. We need to ensure the next measurement is from a different interval to avoid stale readings.\n","thinkingSignature":"930e1cd7790cdb071c04d81184fb30cff7be03f4d3401999a78ad933b99cb41e"},{"type":"text","text":"\n\n\n🧑🏼‍💻 เห็นเลยครับ — Task Manager 33% แต่ overlay แสดง 16%\n\n**สาเหตุ:** drain ค้างจน queue Empty เลยได้ค่าเก่า\n\n**แก้:** ถ้า queue ว่าง ให้รอ 0.05s ให้ thread วัดทัน แล้วค่อยดึงค่าใหม่\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_jb4amdt82oto_1","name":"edit","arguments":{"edits":[{"newText":"def get_cpu_win():\n    _ensure_cpu_thread()\n    try:\n        latest = None\n        while True:\n            try:\n                latest = _q.get_nowait()\n            except queue.Empty:\n                if latest is not None:\n                    break\n                # queue still empty — give thread a moment to finish its 1s block\n                import time as _time; _time.sleep(0.05)\n                try: latest = _q.get_nowait()\n                except queue.Empty: break\n                break\n        return round(latest, 1) if latest is not None else 0\n    except:\n        return 0","oldText":"    try:\n        # drain all stale reads, keep only the latest\n        latest = None\n        while True:\n            try: latest = _q.get_nowait(); break\n            except queue.Empty:\n                import time as _time; _time.sleep(0.05)\n        return round(v, 1) if v is not None else 0\n    except:\n        pass\n    return 0"}],"path":"/home/apinan/.openclaw/workspace/sysmon.py"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":219,"output":1010,"cacheRead":147424,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":148653,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1778172291641,"responseId":"064bf485b13289de446033179017f6ba"}}
{"type":"message","id":"a5164264","parentId":"52ef04a9","timestamp":"2026-05-07T16:45:10.024Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_jb4amdt82oto_1","toolName":"edit","content":[{"type":"text","text":"{\n  \"status\": \"error\",\n  \"tool\": \"edit\",\n  \"error\": \"Could not find the exact text in /home/apinan/.openclaw/workspace/sysmon.py. The old text must match exactly including all whitespace and newlines.\\nCurrent file contents:\\n#!/usr/bin/env python3\\n\\\"\\\"\\\"Floating CPU/GPU monitor — always-on-top overlay.\\\"\\\"\\\"\\nimport sys, os, time, threading, queue\\n\\nIS_WINDOWS = os.name == \\\"nt\\\"\\n\\n# ── CPU reader thread: fresh 1s reading every iteration ──\\n_q = queue.Queue()\\ndef _reader():\\n    import psutil\\n    while True:\\n        # blocks exactly 1s → gives accurate system-wide %\\n        _q.put(psutil.cpu_percent(interval=1))\\n\\n_cpu_started = False\\ndef _ensure_cpu_thread():\\n    global _cpu_started\\n    if not _cpu_started:\\n        t = threading.Thread(target=_reader, daemon=True)\\n        t.start()\\n        _cpu_started = True\\n\\n# ── Windows CPU ──\\ndef get_cpu_win():\\n    _ensure_cpu_thread()\\n    try:\\n        # drain all stale reads, keep only the latest\\n        latest = None\\n        while True:\\n            try: latest = _q.get_nowait()\\n    \\n... (truncated)\"\n}"}],"details":{"status":"error","tool":"edit","error":"Could not find the exact text in /home/apinan/.openclaw/workspace/sysmon.py. The old text must match exactly including all whitespace and newlines.\nCurrent file contents:\n#!/usr/bin/env python3\n\"\"\"Floating CPU/GPU monitor — always-on-top overlay.\"\"\"\nimport sys, os, time, threading, queue\n\nIS_WINDOWS = os.name == \"nt\"\n\n# ── CPU reader thread: fresh 1s reading every iteration ──\n_q = queue.Queue()\ndef _reader():\n    import psutil\n    while True:\n        # blocks exactly 1s → gives accurate system-wide %\n        _q.put(psutil.cpu_percent(interval=1)