{"type":"custom_message","customType":"openclaw.runtime-context","content":"Conversation info (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"chat_id\": \"telegram:1060942816\",\n  \"message_id\": \"6773\",\n  \"sender_id\": \"1060942816\",\n  \"sender\": \"▫️\",\n  \"timestamp\": \"Thu 2026-05-07 23:56 GMT+7\"\n}\n```\n\nSender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"▫️ (1060942816)\",\n  \"id\": \"1060942816\",\n  \"name\": \"▫️\",\n  \"username\": \"robberzaz\"\n}\n```","display":false,"details":{"source":"openclaw-runtime-context"},"id":"92884222","parentId":"0e29e720","timestamp":"2026-05-07T16:56:21.591Z"}
{"type":"message","id":"e8f08893","parentId":"92884222","timestamp":"2026-05-07T16:56:44.200Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The CPU percentage still doesn't match Task Manager. Let me think about what might be different.\n\nThe issue might be:\n1. `GetSystemTimes` returns values in 100-nanosecond intervals, and I'm computing `busy_delta / total_delta * 100`\n2. Task Manager shows overall CPU as a percentage across all cores\n\nWait - `GetSystemTimes` is per-core. Let me check if this is the issue.\n\nActually, looking at the WMI test output earlier - it showed `PercentProcessorTime: 9` which matched the psutil test of `54` that looked wrong...\n\nWait actually when I ran the ctypes test it returned `54` which was much more reasonable for the system load at that time.\n \nI'm wondering if the timing of my samples is the culprit. When I call `get_cpu_win()`, I'm draining the queue and returning the most recent value, but if the thread is still on its first iteration and hasn't collected enough deltas yet, I'd get nothing. The real issue might be that Task Manager uses a different sampling strategy - it could be averaging over a longer window or sampling at a different frequency than my 1-second interval.\n\nActually, thinking about this more carefully: `GetSystemTimes` returns cumulative tick counts since system boot, so when I compute the delta between two samples, I'm getting the fraction of time the CPU was busy versus idle. For a multi-core system, if I'm seeing 50% on an 8-core CPU, that could mean 4 cores were fully busy while the other 4 were idle, which would show up as 50% in Task Manager too.\n\nWait, but `GetSystemTimes` is documented as reporting per-processor time, not aggregated across all cores. The `_Total` instance in `Win32_PerfFormattedData_PerfOS_Processor` should be the aggregate, and that's what I need to match what Task Manager displays.\n\nSince I can't reliably reproduce the issue through conversation, I should ask the user to send me a screenshot showing both the current overlay value and what Task Manager displays, along with the exact PID so I can verify which process version is running.\n","thinkingSignature":"357979b36d97b4e9c385051f92932fa3d19bda6211066d5b88c5d53a317c7012"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_i4fp3l087hh6_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"\"/mnt/c/Windows/System32/WindowsPowerShell/v1.0/powershell.exe\" -Command \"\n\\$py = 'C:\\Users\\Apinan\\AppData\\Local\\Programs\\Python\\Python312\\python.exe'\n\\$tmp = Join-Path \\$env:TEMP 'ctypes_test2.py'\nSet-Content -Path \\$tmp -Value @'\nimport ctypes, time\n\nclass FILETIME(ctypes.Structure):\n    _fields_ = [(\\\"dwLowDateTime\\\", ctypes.c_ulong), (\\\"dwHighDateTime\\\", ctypes.c_ulong)]\n\ndef get_system_times():\n    kernel32 = ctypes.windll.kernel32\n    idle = FILETIME(); kern = FILETIME(); user = FILETIME()\n    kernel32.GetSystemTimes(ctypes.byref(idle), ctypes.byref(kern), ctypes.byref(user))\n    idle_ns   = idle.dwHighDateTime * (2**32) * 10**7 + idle.dwLowDateTime * 10**7\n    kernel_ns = kern.dwHighDateTime * (2**32) * 10**7 + kern.dwLowDateTime * 10**7\n    user_ns   = user.dwHighDateTime * (2**32) * 10**7 + user.dwLowDateTime * 10**7\n    busy_ns   = kernel_ns + user_ns\n    total_ns  = idle_ns + kernel_ns + user_ns\n    return idle_ns, total_ns, busy_ns\n\n# baseline\nidle1, total1, busy1 = get_system_times()\ntime.sleep(1)\n# sample 1\nidle2, total2, busy2 = get_system_times()\nbd1 = busy2 - busy1\ntd1 = total2 - total1\ncpu1 = 100.0 * bd1 / td1 if td1 > 0 else 0\n\ntime.sleep(1)\n# sample 2\nidle3, total3, busy3 = get_system_times()\nbd2 = busy3 - busy2\ntd2 = total3 - total2\ncpu2 = 100.0 * bd2 / td2 if td2 > 0 else 0\n\nprint('sample1=' + str(int(round(cpu1))) + ' sample2=' + str(int(round(cpu2))))\n'@ -Encoding utf8\n& \\$py \\$tmp\nRemove-Item \\$tmp -EA SilentlyContinue\n\" 2>&1"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":3551,"output":983,"cacheRead":45376,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":49910,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1778172981592,"responseId":"064bf73945fabf7e5bb628fdb39431e7"}}
