{"type":"message","id":"4ff6b666","parentId":"e0731188","timestamp":"2026-05-07T16:57:28.204Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Ah, I used `round` as a variable name which shadows the built-in `round` function. Let me fix the diag script.\n","thinkingSignature":"b1169d2d79d0ce4169e9dbaa5d6dac961c5bf8d6f67c6e01b483808685159878"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_zcky6r2zosk8_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"\"/mnt/c/Windows/System32/WindowsPowerShell/v1.0/powershell.exe\" -Command \"\n\\$py = 'C:\\Users\\Apinan\\AppData\\Local\\Programs\\Python\\Python312\\python.exe'\n\\$tmp = Join-Path \\$env:TEMP 'diag2.py'\nSet-Content -Path \\$tmp -Value @'\nimport ctypes, time\n\nclass FILETIME(ctypes.Structure):\n    _fields_ = [(\\\"dwLowDateTime\\\", ctypes.c_ulong), (\\\"dwHighDateTime\\\", ctypes.c_ulong)]\n\n_cpu_idle = _cpu_total = _cpu_busy = 0\n\ndef init():\n    global _cpu_idle, _cpu_total, _cpu_busy\n    k32 = ctypes.windll.kernel32\n    i = FILETIME(); k = FILETIME(); u = FILETIME()\n    k32.GetSystemTimes(ctypes.byref(i), ctypes.byref(k), ctypes.byref(u))\n    _cpu_idle  = i.dwHighDateTime*(2**32)*10**7 + i.dwLowDateTime*10**7\n    _cpu_total = k.dwHighDateTime*(2**32)*10**7 + k.dwLowDateTime*10**7\n    _cpu_busy  = u.dwHighDateTime*(2**32)*10**7 + u.dwLowDateTime*10**7\n\ndef sample():\n    global _cpu_idle, _cpu_total, _cpu_busy\n    k32 = ctypes.windll.kernel32\n    i = FILETIME(); k = FILETIME(); u = FILETIME()\n    k32.GetSystemTimes(ctypes.byref(i), ctypes.byref(k), ctypes.byref(u))\n    idle_ns  = i.dwHighDateTime*(2**32)*10**7 + i.dwLowDateTime*10**7\n    kern_ns  = k.dwHighDateTime*(2**32)*10**7 + k.dwLowDateTime*10**7\n    user_ns  = u.dwHighDateTime*(2**32)*10**7 + u.dwLowDateTime*10**7\n    busy_ns  = kern_ns + user_ns\n    total_ns = idle_ns + kern_ns + user_ns\n    if total_ns > _cpu_total:\n        bd = busy_ns - _cpu_busy\n        td = total_ns - _cpu_total\n        _cpu_busy = busy_ns; _cpu_total = total_ns\n        if td > 0:\n            return 100.0 * bd / td\n    return None\n\ninit()\ntime.sleep(1.1)\nfor n in range(5):\n    v = sample()\n    if v is not None:\n        print('n=' + str(n) + ' raw=' + str(round(v,1)) + ' int=' + str(int(v)))\n    time.sleep(1)\n'@ -Encoding utf8\n& \\$py \\$tmp\nRemove-Item \\$tmp -EA SilentlyContinue\n\" 2>&1"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":1009,"output":705,"cacheRead":49408,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":51122,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1778173037083,"responseId":"064bf76ffbbe44c06eaba451dfc7c13b"}}
{"type":"message","id":"abf5bab6","parentId":"4ff6b666","timestamp":"2026-05-07T16:57:35.981Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_zcky6r2zosk8_1","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"n=0 raw=101.9 int=101\r\nn=1 raw=50.6 int=50\r\nn=2 raw=52.2 int=52\r\nn=3 raw=53.3 int=53\r\nn=4 raw=50.8 int=50"}],"details":{"status":"completed","exitCode":0,"durationMs":7763,"aggregated":"n=0 raw=101.9 int=101\r\nn=1 raw=50.6 int=50\r\nn=2 raw=52.2 int=52\r\nn=3 raw=53.3 int=53\r\nn=4 raw=50.8 int=50","cwd":"/home/apinan/.openclaw/workspace"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1778173055980}}
{"type":"message","id":"bbbd77d1","parentId":"abf5bab6","timestamp":"2026-05-07T16:58:20.870Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Interesting! The first sample shows 101.9% which is way off, but subsequent samples (50-53%) are close to Task Manager. The issue is that:\n\n1. The first sample after init() is wrong (101.9%) - the timing between init() and first sample might not be exactly 1 second, causing inaccuracy\n2. The subsequent samples (50, 52, 53%) are close to Task Manager\n\nThe issue in the sysmon.py code might be that the thread initialization and the queue-based system is introducing drift. \n\nLooking at the sysmon.py code:\n- `_cpu_thread_fn` calls `_init_cpu()` then sleeps 1 second, then starts the loop\n\n\n- Each iteration calls `_sample_cpu()` which uses delta-based calculation\n\nThe real problem is that `_sample_cpu` returns None if there's no progress, and the queue only stores non-None values. So if the thread hasn't collected a fresh reading by the time `get_cpu_win()` drains the queue, it returns 0 and shows \"--\". After the thread starts, there's a 1-second blocking sleep before the first reading, then the queue fills with samples every second. The main thread's `get_cpu_win()` drains all available values and returns the most recent one, which should work correctly in theory.\n\nBut the user says it still shows incorrect percentages. Looking back at the code more carefully, I notice `_sample_cpu()` calculates delta values but doesn't actually store them anywhere—the deltas are computed but then lost because `_cpu_lock` isn't being used to protect the state updates.\n\nWait, actually checking again: the busy and total values are being stored back into the globals. So the logic does save the deltas. The problem might be that the window is showing stale data from when the thread was first initializing, or there's a timing issue where the first sample after `_init_cpu()` is getting discarded.\n\nActually, I'm noticing something—the `_cpu_q.put(v)` only happens when `_sample_cpu()` returns a non-None value. But in the main loop, I'm draining the queue and keeping only the last value. If the thread is putting values faster than they're being consumed, or if there's a mismatch between when values are put and when they're read, that could explain the stale readings.\n\nThe real issue might be that `get_cpu_win()` drains the queue completely but then returns 0 if nothing was available, while the tkinter label keeps showing whatever the last value was. So if the queue empties between updates, the display freezes at the last reading instead of showing current data.\n\nBut the user said the display is actually showing wrong percentages, not frozen ones. Looking at the task manager values (33% and 57%) versus what the script reports (50-53%), there's a consistent 3-17% gap. The problem might be that the thread takes 1 second to initialize, then tkinter starts, but when it calls `get_cpu_win()` right away, the queue is still empty and the function returns 0 instead of waiting for the thread to populate the queue.\n\nThe real issue could be that `get_cpu_win()` drains the queue too aggressively—it keeps pulling values until the queue is empty, so if multiple values accumulate between tkinter updates, it only keeps the last one. But tkinter's `after(500, update)` schedules updates every second, so if a value sits in the queue for longer than expected, it might be getting overwritten rather than displayed.\n\nI think the simplest fix is to have `get_cpu_win()` return the most recent value without draining the queue, so subsequent calls within the same second can still access it. I could use a shared variable protected by a lock to store the latest reading, then have the background thread update it while the main thread reads it directly without removing values from a queue.\n\nImplementing this now...\n","thinkingSignature":"16d7105bebfd97e30fa91f0f7be3141734078a7e9954fca26406ff2f25e10f5d"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_2fetiw40ld2l_1","name":"write","arguments":{"content":"#!/usr/bin/env python3\n\"\"\"Floating CPU/GPU monitor — always-on-top overlay.\"\"\"\nimport sys, os, time, threading, queue\n\nIS_WINDOWS = os.name == \"nt\"\n\n# ── Windows CPU via ctypes GetSystemTimes (same source as Task Manager) ──\nif IS_WINDOWS:\n    import ctypes\n\n    class FILETIME(ctypes.Structure):\n        _fields_ = [(\"dwLowDateTime\", ctypes.c_ulong), (\"dwHighDateTime\", ctypes.c_ulong)]\n\n    _cpu_idle  = 0\n    _cpu_total = 0\n    _cpu_busy  = 0\n    _cpu_val   = 0.0\n    _cpu_lock  = threading.Lock()\n\n    def _init_cpu():\n        global _cpu_idle, _cpu_total, _cpu_busy\n        k32 = ctypes.windll.kernel32\n        i = FILETIME(); k = FILETIME(); u = FILETIME()\n        k32.GetSystemTimes(ctypes.byref(i), ctypes.byref(k), ctypes.byref(u))\n        _cpu_idle  = i.dwHighDateTime*(2**32)*10**7 + i.dwLowDateTime*10**7\n        _cpu_total = k.dwHighDateTime*(2**32)*10**7 + k.dwLowDateTime*10**7\n        _cpu_busy  = u.dwHighDateTime*(2**32)*10**7 + u.dwLowDateTime*10**7\n\n    def _sample_cpu():\n        global _cpu_idle, _cpu_total, _cpu_busy, _cpu_val\n        k32 = ctypes.windll.kernel32\n        i = FILETIME(); k = FILETIME(); u = FILETIME()\n        k32.GetSystemTimes(ctypes.byref(i), ctypes.byref(k), ctypes.byref(u))\n        idle_ns  = i.dwHighDateTime*(2**32)*10**7 + i.dwLowDateTime*10**7\n        kern_ns  = k.dwHighDateTime*(2**32)*10**7 + k.dwLowDateTime*10**7\n        user_ns  = u.dwHighDateTime*(2**32)*10**7 + u.dwLowDateTime*10**7\n        busy_ns  = kern_ns + user_ns\n        total_ns = idle_ns + kern_ns + user_ns\n        with _cpu_lock:\n            if total_ns > _cpu_total:\n                bd = busy_ns - _cpu_busy\n                td = total_ns - _cpu_total\n                _cpu_busy  = busy_ns\n                _cpu_total = total_ns\n                if td > 0:\n                    _cpu_val = 100.0 * bd / td\n\n    _cpu_t = None\n\n    def _cpu_thread_fn():\n        _init_cpu()\n        time.sleep(1.2)   # wait for first accurate 1s window\n        while True:\n            _sample_cpu()\n            time.sleep(1)\n\n    def _ensure_cpu():\n        global _cpu_t\n        if _cpu_t is None or not _cpu_t.is_alive():\n            _cpu_t = threading.Thread(target=_cpu_thread_fn, daemon=True)\n            _cpu_t.start()\n\n    def get_cpu_win():\n        _ensure_cpu()\n        with _cpu_lock:\n            return int(round(_cpu_val))\nelse:\n    def get_cpu_win():\n        import psutil\n        return int(psutil.cpu_percent(interval=1))\n\n# ── Top CPU process ──\ndef get_top_cpu_proc():\n    try:\n        import psutil\n        procs = []\n        for p in psutil.process_iter([\"name\", \"cpu_percent\"]):\n            try:\n                c = p.cpu_percent(interval=0.1)\n                if c > 0.5:\n                    procs.append((c, p.name()))\n            except:\n                pass\n        procs.sort(key=lambda x: x[0], reverse=True)\n        if procs:\n            return procs[0][1][:20]\n    except:\n        pass\n    return \"---\"\n\n# ── GPU via pynvml ──\n_gpu_init_ok = False\ndef _init_gpu():\n    global _gpu_init_ok\n    if not _gpu_init_ok:\n        try:\n            import pynvml\n            pynvml.nvmlInit()\n            _gpu_init_ok = True\n        except Exception:\n            _gpu_init_ok = False\n    return _gpu_init_ok\n\ndef get_gpu_info():\n    if not _init_gpu():\n        return None, \"---\"\n    try:\n        import pynvml\n        h = pynvml.nvmlDeviceGetHandleByIndex(0)\n        util = pynvml.nvmlDeviceGetUtilizationRates(h)\n        gpu_pct = int(util.gpu)\n    except Exception:\n        return None, \"---\"\n    try:\n        import subprocess\n        r = subprocess.getoutput(\n            \"cmd /c nvidia-smi --query-compute-apps=pid,process_name,used_memory --format=csv,noheader 2>nul\"\n        )\n        lines = [l.strip() for l in r.strip().splitlines() if l.strip()]\n        named = []\n        for line in lines:\n            parts = line.split(\",\")\n            if len(parts) < 3:\n                continue\n            name = parts[1].strip()\n            mem_str = parts[2].strip()\n            if not name or name in (\"[Insufficient Permissions]\", \"[N/A]\"):\n                continue\n            if mem_str in (\"[N/A]\", \"0\"):\n                continue\n            if \"\\\\\" in name:\n                name = name.split(\"\\\\\")[-1]\n            mem_val = 0\n            try:\n                if \"MiB\" in mem_str:\n                    mem_val = int(mem_str.split()[0])\n                elif \"GiB\" in mem_str:\n                    mem_val = int(float(mem_str.split()[0]) * 1024)\n            except:\n                pass\n            named.append((mem_val, name[:20]))\n        named.sort(key=lambda x: x[0], reverse=True)\n        seen = set()\n        unique = []\n        for m, n in named:\n            if m > 0 and n.lower() not in seen:\n                seen.add(n.lower())\n                unique.append(n)\n        return gpu_pct, unique[0] if unique else \"---\"\n    except Exception:\n        return gpu_pct, \"---\"\n\ndef pct_col(p):\n    if p is None:\n        return \"#888888\"\n    return \"#ff2222\" if p >= 90 else \"#ff8800\" if p >= 70 else \"#00ff88\"\n\ndef windows_overlay():\n    import tkinter as tk\n\n    root = tk.Tk()\n    root.overrideredirect(True)\n    root.attributes(\"-topmost\", True)\n    root.configure(bg=\"#111111\")\n\n    mon2_w, mon2_h = 1536, 864\n    W, H = 260, 130\n    x = 1536 + (mon2_w - W) - 20\n    y = 20\n    root.geometry(\"{0}x{1}+{2}+{3}\".format(W, H, x, y))\n\n    def ds(e):\n        root._x, root._y = e.x, e.y\n    def dm(e):\n        root.geometry(\"+{0}+{1}\".format(e.x_root - root._x, e.y_root - root._y))\n    root.bind(\"<Button-1>\", ds)\n    root.bind(\"<B1-Motion>\", dm)\n\n    font = (\"Consolas\", 16, \"bold\")\n    sub = (\"Consolas\", 12)\n\n    cpu_lbl = tk.Label(root, text=\"CPU : --\", bg=\"#111111\", fg=\"#00ff88\",\n                       font=font, anchor=\"w\", padx=10, pady=3, relief=\"flat\", bd=0)\n    cpu_lbl.pack(fill=\"x\")\n\n    cpu_name_lbl = tk.Label(root, text=\"---\", bg=\"#111111\", fg=\"#00ccff\",\n                             font=sub, anchor=\"w\", padx=10, pady=3, relief=\"flat\", bd=0)\n    cpu_name_lbl.pack(fill=\"x\")\n\n    gpu_lbl = tk.Label(root, text=\"GPU : --\", bg=\"#111111\", fg=\"#ff8800\",\n                       font=font, anchor=\"w\", padx=10, pady=3, relief=\"flat\", bd=0)\n    gpu_lbl.pack(fill=\"x\")\n\n    gpu_name_lbl = tk.Label(root, text=\"---\", bg=\"#111111\", fg=\"#ff8800\",\n                              font=sub, anchor=\"w\", padx=10, pady=3, relief=\"flat\", bd=0)\n    gpu_name_lbl.pack(fill=\"x\")\n\n    def update():\n        cpu = get_cpu_win()\n        cpu_name = get_top_cpu_proc()\n        gpu, gpu_name = get_gpu_info()\n\n        cpu_lbl.config(text=\"CPU : \" + str(cpu) + \"%\", fg=pct_col(cpu))\n        cpu_name_lbl.config(text=cpu_name)\n        if gpu is not None:\n            gpu_lbl.config(text=\"GPU : \" + str(gpu) + \"%\", fg=pct_col(gpu))\n            gpu_name_lbl.config(text=gpu_name)\n        else:\n            gpu_lbl.config(text=\"GPU : N/A\", fg=\"#888888\")\n            gpu_name_lbl.config(text=\"\")\n\n        root.after(1000, update)\n\n    root.after(500, update)\n    root.mainloop()\n\nif __name__ == \"__main__\":\n    if IS_WINDOWS:\n        windows_overlay()\n    else:\n        print(\"CPU/GPU monitor (Ctrl+C to exit)\")\n        while True:\n            cpu = get_cpu_win()\n            gpu, gn = get_gpu_info()\n            cpu_name = get_top_cpu_proc()\n            g = \" GPU \" + str(gpu) + \"% (\" + gn + \")\" if gpu is not None else \" GPU  N/A\"\n            print(\"  \" + time.strftime(\"%H:%M:%S\") + \"  CPU \" + str(cpu) + \"% (\" + cpu_name + \")\" + g)\n            time.sleep(1)","path":"/home/apinan/.openclaw/workspace/sysmon.py"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":862,"output":3020,"cacheRead":50304,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":54186,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1778173055982,"responseId":"064bf782ea971ebaafb49deedba6aa47"}}
