{"type":"message","id":"653d825b","parentId":"ecac96be","timestamp":"2026-05-07T17:24:50.267Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a much better understanding. Let me look at the key part - how OpenClaw matches skills to user requests. The key text is:\n\n> \"OpenClaw snapshots the eligible skills **when a session starts** and reuses that list for subsequent turns in the same session\"\n\nAnd:\n\n> \"When skills are eligible, OpenClaw injects a compact XML list of available skills into the system prompt (via `formatSkillsForPrompt`\"\n\nThe key insight is that OpenClaw does NOT automatically match skills to user requests. Instead, it:\n1. Builds a list of eligible skills at session start\n\n\n2. Injects that list into the system prompt\n3. Relies on the model (me) to decide when to use which skill based on the description\n\nSo the \"intelligence\" is supposed to come from me reading the description and deciding. But OpenClaw doesn't have built-in LLM routing or automatic skill matching based on user input. The user is asking if there's a smarter way to do this automatically - and based on the docs, the answer is basically \"no, it relies on the model's judgment.\"\n\nWhat I could do though is explore whether OpenClaw has any kind of intent detection or request classification that might help with this, or if there are other configuration options I haven't considered yet.","thinkingSignature":"eaa230281f6cc1ed506f008565181fe54e6b9c3ee3e75d909cc77e1096f5bbf0"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_0hd4n78arjwp_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"grep -n \"intent\\|classif\\|rout\\|match\\|detect\\|keyword\" -i /home/apinan/.hermes/node/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/tools/skills.md | head -20"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":65216,"output":336,"cacheRead":24250,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":89802,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"tota